❶ Are you focused & honed in on your social networks? ⁣

Day 42: The Covidmaid’s Tale... #StayHome #TheCovidmaidsTale #OfCovid #UnderItsMask #BlessedBeTheToiletPaper #MayTheDoorOpen ( Inspired by @handmaidsonhulu & @therealmargaretatwood ) . . .

A Mask.
Some Gloves.
Some Hand sanitizer.
Bacterial wipes by every door.
There’s an air purifier with multiple settings. 
But It’s not household dust
they’re afraid of, Its those other particles,
The airborne ones, the germs. 
I try not to think about, 
how they’re floating all around me.
It’s harder when the news is on.
Watching the news can 
hurt your chances.
My name is Ofcovid.
I am an essential worker.
There are other jobs, 
but they’re forbidden now. 
So many things are forbidden now...

The COVID-19 Public Records Project is one of five projects receiving funds as part of the JSK 2020 Journalism Challenge on COVID-19. 
This is a collaborative effort to respond to community information needs, and monitor human rights during the #COVID19 pandemic and recovery in Detroit, Milwaukee, and other cities around the US.

The project will employ freelancers and collect critical public records at the local level.

Matt Kiefer, a 2020 JSK Fellow, is partnering with Garance Burke, 2020 JSK Fellow; Sarah Alvarez, founder of Outlier Media and 2016 JSK Fellow; and Michael Morisy, founder of MuckRock Foundation and 2015 JSK Fellow.

My kids were asking me last night, “why do we put a stent in the heart when someone has heart disease?” Because calcification has blocked the blood from traveling on its normal path to the heart and the stent is an added path for the blood to get there.
Heart disease doesn’t just show up one day. It’s a storm caused by sugar, seed oils, smoking, stress, and genetics. There’s a test you can take called the Calcium Score to show how well your arteries are feeding blood to your heart.

Recently, scientists have been discussing another measure to support immune and respiratory health: Vitamin D. -

Vitamin D is associated with keeping your body's systems running smoothly. -

The most common way to get vitamin D is sun exposure. You can also get vitamin D from food and supplements. -

Aim for Vitamin D levels over 30 ng/mL, but not more than 80 ng/mL. You can ask your provider to test your levels. -

The man accused of making the sickening videos, Fan Yuanqing, has been expelled from Shandong University of Technology, according to a Weibo post by the university — but he has not been criminally charged. The person responsible for such heinous acts belongs behind bars, where they cannot harm other animals or people. Have you been feeling frustrated recently with having to stay home because of the pandemic?
Have you been wishing that the world could just "go back to normal"?
I can assure you I have at times. I have wished for a day where we don't have to stay in quarantine. I have wished for the world to be "normal" again.
But, while wishing all of this, I have thought of the millions of animals who are born into a life of lockdown.
Where all they know is living inside a cage or four walls. Where many of them only see the sunshine once they are inside a transport truck headed to slaughter. Then they are locked down and restrained so that a knife can be forced into their throat.
The animals have never been given a break from being in lockdown, and while we deal with this pandemic, animals are still being bred and forced down the kill floor.
NOW I ASK YOU: Are you responsible for animals being forced into a life in lockdown while you are in quarantine?
Are you choosing to eat the bodies and secretions of animals knowing that by doing so, you are forcing them onto the kill floor?
.
.

You’d think I’ve had enough trying to stay sane and as humanly focused as possible during this pandemic- well I’d thought so too- guess we don’t always know what we’ll be doing until we’re tested, and that’s exactly what this book  is, a solo act of competence (haha).
🦠
🦠
Never had I heard of Mary Mallon and her mysteriously miserable living experience with Typhoid Fever, that’s how little to nothing I read of historical fiction. Mallon is a woman who has a “normal” life as she serves as a cook for a group of the elite members of society in New York City, she has a relationship with a man named Alfred and they are learning to live together in the walls of a small apartment until the day everything shifts. Mary is pulled by authorities and taken miles away into confinement after numerous people contract and others die from Thypoid Fever- all as a consequence of her cooking, to which she’s been labeled as “asymptomatic carrier”.
🦠
🦠
I went into this read highly intrigued by the police and judicial trial and adversities Mallon had to face, truth be told I needed more, the only reason I pushed through two sections was because I made a commitment to finish it and so I did.
.
.

Ever since our world was turned upside down a few weeks ago I’ve seen everyday people put on their armor and go into battle. Simple tasks like delivering mail has become a heroic effort. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Overnight everyone was asked to battle. ⁣⁣
Overnight everyone became Warriors. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I wanted to get involved and contribute so I got to work in the studio and I want to dedicate this to all of you. I re-recorded Warrior to reflect our current world and all the amazing heroic things you’re all doing. To all the hospital workers, postal service people, grocery store workers, police and firemen, every single one of you who has had their world shaken. This is for you.⁣⁣
⁣⁣

Our 9 Tower family has lost our beloved colleague and friend, Alex Ofori, to COVID-19. Our hearts are heavy with grief.

As a coworker, Alex was everything you could ask for and then some. He always greeted us with a cheery hello at the beginning of his shift, and wished us safe home at the end of ours. He knew what any one of us needed almost before we asked. He worked hard even under the most difficult circumstances and he never complained, not only because he felt a deep loyalty to his colleagues, but because he was called to provide the utmost professional and compassionate care for his patients.

Outside of work, Alex was a devoted family man who valued his wife and children more than anything. I have been told that the Alex we knew at work was the same Alex his family knew—a kind man with a caring heart who gave his all to those he loved most.

Thank you, Alex, for being YOU. For making us laugh, for giving us strength, for helping us feel safe. We are all better care providers for having worked alongside you, and for having watched you work with your patients. It was an honor to work with you and a privilege to know you. You are OUR hero.

We are asking anyone who can spare it to please donate to a GoFundMe that was established in his name to provide for his family in the difficult time: 
https://www.gofundme.com/f/oofori-family-fund

"My husband and I have been actively involved in all things rescue related for the last 6 years including transporting countless pups, fostering and consequently foster failing. Most recently we've taken on a new venture when we decided to say YES to our 7-years-young pandemic pup, Lady (formerly known as Suzie). Throughout the COVID-19 pandemic, my Facebook feed had been inundated with dogs that HAD to come out of county shelters here in NC or they were put on the 'list'. Shelters were closing with the state-wide stay-at-home order, the dogs had no choice but to go into foster care or cross the rainbow bridge. It was a heartbreaking reality but also soooooo humbling to see so many people stepping up and helping the delicate situation at hand. 
One pup, in particular, I couldn't seem to get off my radar. Her name was Suzie (how fitting right?!) and she was in the Duplin County Animal Services in NC. The shelter had released a statement stating that all dogs at the DCAS had to go into a foster home and that volunteers were no longer going to be allowed in the shelter because of the state-wide mandate. I watched the site closely to see if anyone showed interest in Suzie, but they didn't. Every volunteer at the shelter had the same thing to say about Suzie, she was 'the sweetest pup', 'constantly wagging her tail', 'just wanted a good head rub or belly scratch', and would 'love to lay in your lap' if you allowed it! It was a Thursday afternoon and a volunteer at the shelter who I had been in close contact with days prior informed me that Suzie would be euthanized if she was not adopted or had foster commitment by the end of the day Friday. It was at that moment that I knew I COULD NOT let her live out her days in a cold shelter, not knowing if she was loved. 
Three weeks later and we have the MOST loving, affectionate, 7-year old girl fittingly now named 'Lady'. I never thought I'd be here saying that we adopted a senior pup, but WOW does it feel good. I don't know what her 6 years before us looked like, but I swear it's as though she's showing her appreciation for what we did with each kiss she gives or cuddle on the couch! -Dominique" ❤️ #seniordog

The four current exec members are all graduating and have been working hard to keep things running smoothly and transition to a new board for next year through this time of uncertainty so look at for in the coming weeks things for all four of us as well as things about the new execs that are taking over 😁

To start off the exec board appreciation there’s me, Sarah, your social media and promotions officer. Psychology major. Sociology minor. Plans? Who knows, especially now… I’ve been an active member of HPS for three years and its been the best three years. I’ve met some of my best friends through this club and wish it didn’t have to come to an end. I hate how this semester had to end and hope to see everyone at some point in the future because until I officially graduate, they’ve just postponed it so I’m holding out hope, I’m not anywhere near done with this club and that’s not even a guarantee then. I love you all and wish you all well in whatever you end up doing 💜

#SaltAndPepperSquid #SaltAndPepperShrimp "quarantine-style"...had no green onions nor jalapenos

I was only able to use what I have on hand. If you have cornstarch or potato starch, the flour will adhere better. I heard that rice flour makes it crispy and other ppl said baking powder do too (from my air fryer FB group). I had tapioca starch vs corn or potato starch. So, here's what I did:

1) Julienne some ginger and put that to aside.

2) Slice some whole garlic and put that to aside.

3) If you have green onions and jalapenos, slice and chop them up.

4) Clean, wash, cut and dry the squid and/or shrimp (I didn't want to bother with shells when eating).
•
5) In a big mixing bowl, mix cornstarch, some rice flour, teaspoon of baking powder, i used seasonal salt, black pepper, garlic powder, and onion powder.

6) Toss the seafood into the flour mixture, making sure everything is fully coated.

7) Deep fry the sliced garlic first and put it to aside.

8) Deep fry all the seafood and place it in a big strainer/colander to drain oil.

9) Heat up a wok really hot, add some oil, stir-fry the ginger until fragrant, add in the deep fried garlic chips and a drizzle of sesame oil. Stir toss stir toss.

10) Add in your jalapenos, green onions, and seafood. Stir toss stir toss. If you want to add more salt and pepper, you can, but I find that my flour mixture was seasoned enough and didn't need to.

11) Once everything is all tossed together, turn off heat and it's done.

Bon Appetit!

Our 9 Tower family has lost our beloved colleague and friend, Alex Ofori, to COVID-19. Our hearts are heavy with grief.

As a coworker, Alex was everything you could ask for and then some. He always greeted us with a cheery hello at the beginning of his shift, and wished us safe home at the end of ours. He knew what any one of us needed almost before we asked. He worked hard even under the most difficult circumstances and he never complained, not only because he felt a deep loyalty to his colleagues, but because he was called to provide the utmost professional and compassionate care for his patients.

Outside of work, Alex was a devoted family man who valued his wife and children more than anything. I have been told that the Alex we knew at work was the same Alex his family knew—a kind man with a caring heart who gave his all to those he loved most.

Thank you, Alex, for being YOU. For making us laugh, for giving us strength, for helping us feel safe. We are all better care providers for having worked alongside you, and for having watched you work with your patients. It was an honor to work with you and a privilege to know you. You are OUR hero.

We are asking anyone who can spare it to please donate to a GoFundMe that was established in his name to provide for his family in the difficult time:

Anyone low on paper products due to #covid19 shortages? You can make your own! 😀 Instead of toilet paper & paper towels cut up old, worn out clothing, blankets, or sheets to use instead. If you have a baby, use cloth wipes & cloth diapers instead of disposable diapers. Instead of Kleenex to blow your nose, use cloth napkins. In place of disposable napkins, use cloth napkins. Although doing this does produce some extra laundry, it really isn't that much AND the savings in not having to buy single use items PLUS the positive environmental impact make it worth it. If you have the means to try even one of these ideas, I encourage you to give it a try. I will confess, we still have some remaining toilet paper which we have been using & saving for bowel movements. Before coronavirus though we weren't even using washable and reusable toilet paper so we are making progress. .

We wanted to give you all an update as far as COVID-19 and what it means for @grr_clothing. 
First off, thank you to everyone who's been patiently waiting for their orders to ship out! Fulfillment times have been longer than usual do to increased levels of demand from our supplier. They're seeing orders come in at levels similar to Black Friday and Cyber Monday.

As a result, fulfillment times can be as long as 13-16 business days. The downside to this increase in demand is longer wait times, but it also shows ecommerce is thriving despite these uncertain times. 
Our supplier is still fulfilling orders and shipping them out, as well as following strict CDC sanitation guidelines and practicing social distancing. They're actually hiring MORE people to help meet the increased demand.

Thank you once again to everyone who's been waiting for their orders to go out. We understand and sympathize with your frustrations. We can't wait to see everyone wearing our stuff!

We wanted to give you all an update as far as COVID-19 and what it means for @grr_clothing. 
First off, thank you to everyone who's been patiently waiting for their orders to ship out! Fulfillment times have been longer than usual do to increased levels of demand from our supplier. They're seeing orders come in at levels similar to Black Friday and Cyber Monday.

As a result, fulfillment times can be as long as 13-16 business days. The downside to this increase in demand is longer wait times, but it also shows ecommerce is thriving despite these uncertain times. 
Our supplier is still fulfilling orders and shipping them out, as well as following strict CDC sanitation guidelines and practicing social distancing. They're actually hiring MORE people to help meet the increased demand.

Thank you once again to everyone who's been waiting for their orders to go out. We understand and sympathize with your frustrations. We can't wait to see everyone wearing our stuff!

I have a first-grade student; by February, he was reading a second-grade level. Today his mother called and asked me concerned he wouldn't be ready for second grade, What if I'm doing this teaching thing wrong? With summer coming up quickly, parents are starting to panic.
The pandemic has completely shifted what it means to be a teacher, fewer academic focus, more listening than ever before.
In this time I'm doing what I can, I'm making the phone calls, sending the emails along with physical mail. As a teacher, I've spent many sleepless nights not only thinking about my students, hoping they're getting the essentials that they need, but thinking about the parents as well, and desperately hoping that they're getting what they need as well. It's a scary and crazy time, and unfortunately, all we can do is hope.

So today the first vaccines for COVID19 have been tested on humans and we are all eager to hear the results. England has been at the forefront of making these vaccines, the University of Oxford leading Phase 1and Imperial College London leading Phase 2. What does this all mean??? —

Phase 1: 
The first time the vaccine is used on humans. It’s usually given to a small group of people. —

Aim: .To get the accurate information regarding the drug eg. dosage, safety and side effects
.To know how the body processes the medication —

Phase 2:
.Tested on a larger group of patients (this can include those that are healthy and those affected. —

Aim: .To know how effective it is on different people and to get a clear understanding of the side effects
.The opportunity to test against a placebo (an inactive drug) —

Phase 3: . Much larger trial, this can have over thousands of people —

Aim: .To show the safety and effectiveness of the drug in patients who are going to use it —

THE DRUG IS FDA APPROVED ✅ —

Phase 4:
.Monitoring the drug after launch —

Aim:
. To review long term safety and cost effectiveness of the drug —

Fun Fact: Usually the development of a drug takes up to 15years were scientists work on a daily basis to understand the strain of the virus and how it’s developing. These scientists have worked extremely hard to develop the vaccine since the genetic code of SARS-COV-2 was shared from China less than 6months ago. As a doctor I’m hopeful that we can control this pandemic. —

More info: NHS website, BBC

What is a social justice doula?⠀
I have a Master’s degree in social work; I am a writer, consultant, third-year doctoral student, former organizer, & anti-racist facilitator. To capture the various work that I do, I have named myself ”the social justice doula.” ⠀
⠀
As a social justice doula, I create & curate the conditions for social justice learning to take place and help people and organizations put their anti-racism into praxis (theory + practice = praxis). ⠀
⠀
Diversity and inclusion are simply not enough if your organization has a social justice mandate or expectation in its mission or vision. ⠀
⠀
This global pandemic has forever disrupted the norm. Ask yourself, can you afford to lead your team and your classroom in the same ways you have been before COVID-19?  Doyou know how to create syllabi and policies that are in service to social justice? If someone asked the Black, Indigenous, people of color (BIPOC) who you supervise, lead, or teach to rate your leadership from an anti-racist standpoint, would you be petrified about the kind of feedback you would get? Do you lead a majority racially homogenous team that wants to be anti-racist? Do you know how to make this happen? Does your leadership reflect your feminist and anti-racist values? If the answer to these questions dissatisfies you in any way, then we should talk. ⠀
⠀
Contact me here via my website (link in bio), where you can learn all about my work and what I offer. The best leaders are honest about their areas of growth and do their best to address it. Let's address it together. ⠀

Do you have a gratitude practice? Did you know that writing down a few things you are thankful for every day or every week has been shown in positive psychology research to help you be more optimistic and feel better about yourself? It can help you feel happier and even help your relationships get a little stronger 🌻 remember you don’t have to be thankful for anything BIG ! On the hardest days dig deep- sometimes being thankful for something small like the sunshine, nice music, or a warm hug can remind you that better days are to come 💛

𝙎𝙚𝙡𝙛 𝘿𝙚𝙥𝙧𝙚𝙘𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙤𝙣: 𝘢𝘤𝘵 𝘰𝘧 𝘳𝘦𝘱𝘳𝘪𝘮𝘢𝘯𝘥𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘰𝘯𝘦𝘴𝘦𝘭𝘧 𝘣𝘺 𝘣𝘦𝘭𝘪𝘵𝘵𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘨, 𝘶𝘯𝘥𝘦𝘳𝘷𝘢𝘭𝘶𝘪𝘯𝘨, 𝘰𝘳 𝘥𝘪𝘴𝘱𝘢𝘳𝘢𝘨𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘰𝘯𝘦𝘴𝘦𝘭𝘧, 𝘰𝘳 𝘣𝘦𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘦𝘹𝘤𝘦𝘴𝘴𝘪𝘷𝘦𝘭𝘺 𝘮𝘰𝘥𝘦𝘴𝘵⁣
⁣
This is something I 𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵𝘁 I was hiding well: from others and from myself. ⁣
Until a conversation I had a few nights ago with someone who KNOWS me. ⁣
⁣
𝘞𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘐 𝘢𝘭𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘥𝘺 𝘬𝘯𝘦𝘸:⁣
•I make jokes to belittle myself ⁣
•I don’t take compliments well because I don’t think I have done anything to deserve them ⁣
•I have shitty self-esteem ⁣
⁣
𝙒𝙝𝙖𝙩 𝙄 𝙖𝙡𝙨𝙤 𝙠𝙣𝙤𝙬 𝙞𝙨 𝙩𝙝𝙖𝙩 𝙢𝙤𝙨𝙩 𝙥𝙚𝙤𝙥𝙡𝙚 𝙝𝙖𝙫𝙚 𝙣𝙤 𝙞𝙙𝙚𝙖 𝙄 𝙛𝙚𝙚𝙡 𝙩𝙝𝙞𝙨 𝙬𝙖𝙮. ⁣
⁣
“𝘐 𝘫𝘶𝘴𝘵 𝘸𝘢𝘯𝘵 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘵𝘰 𝘣𝘦 𝘩𝘢𝘱𝘱𝘺”⁣
I tried to convince myself and them that I was happy but before finishing my sentence we both could sense the lie. ⁣
⁣
⁣
I struggle daily with anxiety and combat my insecurities by making fun of myself first so “others can’t hurt me”⁣
⁣
𝗜 𝘀𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗴𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗱𝗮𝗶𝗹𝘆 with basking in my accomplishments because I don’t want others to think I’m conceited and call me on my flaws. ⁣
⁣
⁣
𝗜 𝘀𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗴𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗱𝗮𝗶𝗹𝘆 with just saying ONE nice thing about myself. ⁣
⁣
But I am determined to change that. ⁣
Starting today. ⁣
⁣
“𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝘀𝗼 𝗺𝘂𝗰𝗵 𝘁𝗼 𝗼𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿; 𝗟𝗼𝘃𝗲, 𝗟𝗲𝗮𝗱𝗲𝗿𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽, 𝗖𝗼𝗺𝗽𝗮𝘀𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻, 𝗞𝗻𝗼𝘄𝗹𝗲𝗱𝗴𝗲 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗳 𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗺 𝘀𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘀𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗯𝗲𝗰𝗮𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲𝗻’𝘁 𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗿𝗻𝗲𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝗹𝗼𝘃𝗲 𝘄𝗵𝗼 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗮𝗿𝗲”⁣
⁣
I’d love to hear your thoughts and feelings about self deprecation and self esteem⁣
If you’re uncomfortable sharing in the comments please feel free to message me. ⁣

O Dr Lair Ribeiro ontem na Live dele explicou que podemos fazer uma análise de como estamos nos sentindo depois que o covid e a quarentena começaram.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Ele sugeriu que nós coloquemos as seguintes qualidades abaixo. E deveríamos agregar um número de 1 a 5, 5 sendo a maior intensidade na qual esse sentimento vem a você, e 1 a menor intensidade.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Ansioso/a⁣⁣
Deprimido/a⁣⁣
Nervoso/a⁣⁣
Sobrecarregado/a⁣⁣
Isolado/a⁣⁣
Entediado/a⁣⁣
Desmotivado/a ⁣⁣
Esfomeado/a⁣⁣
Preocupado/a⁣⁣
Triste⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Atribua um número de 1 a 5 para cada sentimento depois da quarentena e covid. Quando você somar todos os números, se der abaixo de 20 você não está preocupado(a). Se der acima de 40 você realmente tem que pedir ajuda ou mudar as coisas que você lê, vê, e reinventar o que te motiva, quem você quem ser etc.⁣⁣
⁣⁣

Dr Lair Ribeiro yesterday on his live explained that we can do an analysis of how we are feeling after the covid and quarantine started. He suggested that we write down the following qualities below; we should add a number from 1 to 5, 5 being the highest intensity at which that feeling comes to you, and 1 the lowest intensity. ⁣⁣
Anxious ⁣⁣
Depressed ⁣⁣
Nervous ⁣⁣
Overwhelmed ⁣⁣
Isolated ⁣⁣
Bored ⁣⁣
Unmotivated ⁣⁣
Hungry ⁣⁣
Worried ⁣⁣
Sad ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Assign a number from 1 to 5 for each feeling you have experienced after quarantine and covid. When you add up all the numbers, if it goes below 20 you are not worried. If it adds up close to 40, you really have to ask for help or change the things you read, see, and reinvent what motivates you, who you who you are, etc. This way, you will know where you are and where you want to go. Days 5 Mi-cuit chocolate #chocolate #valrhona #desert #pastrychef Quarantine Mi-Cuit Chocolate Valrhona ​ 
Mi-Cuit Chocolate 
8 oz. chocolate Caraibe
1 stick + 2 tbs. Melted butter
4 each eggs yorks
4 each large eggs
2 oz. sugar granulated
1 tbs. all purpose flour 
Melted the chocolate with butter. Mix flour and sugar add eggs yorks and eggs white to the chocolate and butter mixture. Preheat you oven at 375 F garnish you mixture in flexipan mold and bake for 12 minutes and cool down for 2  minutes before you eating the MI-Cuit. 
Ganache Smoke Almond 
½ cup smoked almond with skin
3 ½ oz. Valrhona 66%
2 oz. Jivara chocolate
6 oz. heavy cream
6 oz. maple syrup 
Infuse almond with heavy cream and maple syrup poor into the strainer to the chocolate. Mix rapidly with a spatula to create a smooth and glossy emulsion. Gradually keep adding the cream to the Valrhona Chocolate while mixing maintains the smooth and glossy texture until all cream is incorporated. Keep in room temperature for minimum 12 hours to 24 hours before using.
Dry you almond on fry pan or in oven low temperature and keep for garnish you Mi-Cuit

As the coronavirus #outbreak puts pressure on meat-packing plants and across the world, millions of pigs, chickens, and many other innocent animals are being cruelly put to death in the world farms—with animals being burned or buried alive, intentionally suffocated in layers of foam or by having their ventilation cut off.
_
"We are full to the brim. But when we are down about 23% in hog killing capacity and we can't process at normal rates, then the only option is to #depopulate.- agriculture consultant
_
The term "depopulate" is a meat industry term that refers to the mass killing,, of animals. The methods used to kill the animals are extreme and inhumane. The fact remains that you cannot kill someone that wants to live humanely.
_
Killing methods include water-based foam generators, burning them and burying them alive whole-house gassing and ventilation shutdown-- none of this can be considered humane.

Foaming means covering hens with a layer of foam that blocks their airways, gradually suffocating them over several minutes. Ventilation  shutdown, is considered one of the cruellest, but cheapest options. "Shutting down broiler #chicken house ventilation systems means animals die of organ failure due to overheating, as temperatures quickly rise.Foam is a horribly inhumane way to kill. You can hear their screams as they're suffocating. -
The sheer numbers of animals being killed now is hard to fathom. But we kill over a hundred and fifty billion land animals every year... NEEDLESSLY.

I want to share with you some joyful news. On Monday, I became a father.  This is Wyatt Cooper.  He is three days old. He is named after my father, who died when I was ten.  I hope I can be as good a dad as he was.  My son's middle name is Morgan. It's a family name on my mom's side.  I know my mom and dad liked the name morgan because I recently found a list they made 52 years ago when they were trying to think of names for me.  Wyatt Morgan Cooper.  My son.  He was 7.2 lbs at birth, and he is sweet, and soft, and healthy and I am beyond happy.

As a gay kid, I never thought it would be possible to have a child, and I’m grateful for all those who have paved the way, and for the doctors and nurses and everyone involved in my son's birth. 
Most of all, I am grateful to a remarkable surrogate who carried Wyatt, and watched over him lovingly, and tenderly, and gave birth to him. It is an extraordinary blessing - what she, and all surrogates give to families who cant have children. My surrogate has a beautiful family of her own, a wonderfully supportive husband, and kids, and  I am incredibly thankful for all the support they have given Wyatt and me. My family is blessed to have this family in our lives

I do wish my mom and dad and my brother, Carter, were alive to meet Wyatt, but I like to believe they can see him. I imagine them all together, arms around each other, smiling and laughing, happy to know that their love is alive in me and in Wyatt, and that our family continues.

We had planned to share better news with you this afternoon.

As you might have guessed, we had a second date lined up with our friends at @jojospizzeria to provide doughnuts for home delivery & pickup.

We were bowled over by your response to our announcement on Monday, and wanted to ensure we didn’t go through the whole production run in under half an hour again.

We’re sorry to say that we’ll have to postpone the second production date. Everyone who ordered for May 3rd, don’t worry! You are still going to get the first batch of hot ones from our new kitchen just as you were promised. But a scheduling hiccup in our construction means that our plans for the Mother’s Day weekend have been derailed.

I wanted to give you a peek into where we’re at, presently, because we’ve cycled quickly between completely mum and dropping hints all over the place. When we light the fryers again, it will be in our new headquarters at 1721 St Laurent Boulevard.

We’re putting every lesson we’ve learned in the last eight years into practice, making sure we don’t have a production process that bumps against the ceiling of what we can make do with. We are building some big new systems, and one really important thing for health & safety is the concrete floors we’re having poured.

It just so happens that it is not a GREAT time to schedule services? And the only time we’re able to schedule our pour is right before the weekend in question, unless we want to wait for months.  You don’t want to wait for months any more than we do!

It takes our new space out of commission for about four days… and we’ve already moved our equipment, so we can’t use our old space. We’ve looked at it front, back, upside down, and sideways… and we just have to push back our second production date.

To avoid more disappointment, we’re not going to estimate that date again until we are ready.  That’s why we’ve said so little in the last year that we’ve been working on this… there’s always something at the last minute that turns anticipation into anxiety. (cont'd in comment)

Pork stir fry with ramen noodles recipe This is a pantry dish for sure and a gloriously delicious one, that even the baby loves! .
.
.
THE RECIPE:
Makes 3 adult and 2 baby portions.
To make, saute 2/3 pound ground pork till cooked, drain, set aside. Add 1 tbsp olive oil to pan, saute thinly sliced red bell pepper, carrots, and celery 2 minutes over medium-high heat. Add thinly sliced zucchini, continue cooking till veggies are soft. Meanwhile, in a separate pot, boil two ramen packets of noodles for 3 minutes (don't use the seasoning packet), drain and set aside. Remove from pan, set aside. Return meat to pan, make a well in the center and pour in your sauce (2 tbsp tamari low sodium, 1 tsp rice wine vinegar, 1 tbsp orange juice, 2 tbsp sesame oil, 2 cloves fresh garlic minced, 1 tsp freshly chopped ginger root, 1/4 tsp maple syrup, 1 tsp corn starch). When it bubbles, stir meat and sauce together. Add veggies and noodles, stir till combined. Top with freshly diced green onions and sesame seeds. .
.
.
To serve to baby, remove meat from his portion and chop fine then return to dish. Remove all celery, discard. .
.
.

When the postmortem is done on the media’s coverage of COVID-19 (and it will be), it will be clear that the virus was no Black Plague — it’s not even the flu on a bad year.

SARS-CoV-2, which causes COVID-19, has killed 56,749 Americans as of Tuesday.

That’s not good. But it’s not as bad as the 2017-2018 flu season, when 80,000 -plus perished. And it’s a long cry from what all the experts were warning about just a few weeks ago: First, they predicted 1.7 million Americans dead; then they redid the models (this time apparently entering a few more “facts”) and said 100,000-240,000 dead.

Now, a major model relied on by the White House Coronavirus Task Force predicts about 70,000 dead by the end of August.

And for that we shut down the U.S. economy?! As the coronavirus swept across China, then Europe — then everywhere — the U.S. media breathlessly reported every terrifying number, almost gleefully. Their ratings soared, of course, as they scared the hell out of every American, many of whom have stayed home for the last 40 days, emerging only to buy toilet paper, but even then clad in masks and tiptoeing in fear.

But here are some facts: • Fatality Rate

A recent Stanford University antibody study estimated the fatality rate from the virus is likely 0.1% to 0.2%. The World Health Organization (WHO) had estimated that the death rate was 20 to 30 times higher and called for isolation policies. On which version do you think the media focused?

In New York City, the U.S. epicenter of the pandemic, the death rate for people 18 to 45 years old is 0.01%, or 10 per 100,000 in the population. People aged 75 and older, though, have a death rate 80 times that. For children under 18, the rate of death is zero per 100,000. That’s zero.

More than half of the COVID-19 deaths in Europe occurred in long-term care or nursing-home facilities. At least one-fifth of the deaths recorded in the U.S. so far have occurred there.

Nearly all the patients hospitalized for the coronavirus in New York City had underlying health conditions, according to a recent study. 👉👉👉https://m.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/apr/28/covid-19-turning-out-to-be-huge-hoax-p .

I asked our manager if I could start “spirit days” in our pediatric dialysis unit. Patients and staff are dressing on theme every Friday. •

Did you know that I work in children’s dialysis? Did you know that about 2% of the US population that is on dialysis are children? The kidneys play a vital role in health and life. They filter waste products in the blood as well balance fluid and electrolytes amongst many other things. All these things play a factor in their nutrition. My patients kidneys don’t work, so they have to come for dialysis 3-4 times per week for hours at a time. They would die without it. •

Everything these children hear tells them to stay at home. They can’t go to school, yet they have to come multiple times a week to have their life saving treatment. They also end up overhearing a lot of employees talk about the coronavirus as well as hear the news briefings when members of the staff turn them on. •

We normally have iPads to help keep the patients occupied but they have not been able to be utilized due to the need for sanitization between uses. We can only play games or do crafts with patients that do not require multiple uses for the same reason. Also, with visitor restrictions, to protect them and our staff, many children are not able to have their parent at their side because they have to take care of the other children in the family. •

This patient population is very near and dear to my heart. My office is actually located inside the dialysis unit so I get to see and spend time with these patients every single day.
I wish I could do more for them. We all do. But we can continue to show up every day, show them we’re still here to provide their care. And maybe wear a themed shirt every Friday to bring a little cheer.

Covid-19 & I ⁣ ⁣

Working during this difficult time in ITU is a big thing for me. As its only been 8 months since I qualified as a nurse, I am still learning every day. I knew that working on the frontline I was at risk of being infected with COVID-19. However, I never let it get to me or the way I work, as I love my job and everything about it. As our trust prepared for the surge, our doors were flooding with patients that were COVID-19 positive and required ventilation and other close support and monitoring. ⁣ ⁣

Shifts were getting challenging, ridiculously exhausting day in and day out, work was just very overwhelming. Our breaks were delayed at times as the workload was a lot. Wearing a face mask made my skin damaged and I developed a pressure sore on my nose which has left a mark on my nose. Working in full PPE which our trust provided was tough as majority of the time I would get a headache and feel really hot and sweaty whilst working hard. ⁣ ⁣

At the beginning of April, I started to get a sore throat, as I first felt it, I decided to immediately self- isolate myself. I alerted work and booked myself in for staff swabbing. The next day I developed a fever, this fever lasted around one week with my sore throat. Most of my time being ill was spent in my bed. I could not move literally. I had aches and pain, I felt nauseous at times and lost my senses I couldn’t taste or smell anything which really stressed me out. The night before receiving my swab results, I was so anxious, I couldn’t sleep. ⁣

🦊 Hi everyone - I'm still around. COVID-19 threw me in the deep end of life and I've been barely treading water for 7 weeks. Which unfortunately put stitching and social media to a grinding halt. Even though I had banked up so many of my "meet the maker" posts, I just couldn't stay ahead/keep up and do the whole month.⁠
⁠
Anyway. A few things:⁠
1) Someone tagged me in this #hoopyourself "challenge" and I figured it would be a good returning post to do. So here's my mug in a 6" embroidery hoop 😋⁠
2) I've not touched my stitching supplies in a long time but I can feel the itch coming back. I'm trying not to push it too early as I don't want to completely burn out. So I've been playing a lot of Animal Crossing to unwind in stead. It's horrible timing though, because⁠
3) We're moving to Seattle in less than 2 weeks. Yep, moving again. This time for a much longer period of time (fingers crossed). And yep; moving during an effing pandemic. We've been waiting and waiting for our visa transfer to be submitted; we were expecting to move this coming week!⁠
⁠
As you can probably understand, I'm exhausted, frazzled and SICK 👏 OF 👏 IT 👏 ALL 👏.⁠
⁠
Regarding TLK content: I have a lot of designs that are close to completion (before I dropped everything and went into survival move) and a lot of pieces I have in a queue to work on, so I am hoping to be able to share stuff on here [and other social media outlets] relatively soon.⁠
⁠
Thanks to everyone who's sent messages to check up on me. ♥️ I'm feeling out of the loop a fair bit with my stitchy friends so tell me; what's hip and cool now? 😜 🦊

Covid-19 & I ⁣ ⁣

Working during this difficult time in ITU is a big thing for me. As its only been 8 months since I qualified as a nurse, I am still learning every day. I knew that working on the frontline I was at risk of being infected with COVID-19. However, I never let it get to me or the way I work, as I love my job and everything about it. As our trust prepared for the surge, our doors were flooding with patients that were COVID-19 positive and required ventilation and other close support and monitoring. ⁣ ⁣

Shifts were getting challenging, ridiculously exhausting day in and day out, work was just very overwhelming. Our breaks were delayed at times as the workload was a lot. Wearing a face mask made my skin damaged and I developed a pressure sore on my nose which has left a mark on my nose. Working in full PPE which our trust provided was tough as majority of the time I would get a headache and feel really hot and sweaty whilst working hard. ⁣ ⁣

At the beginning of April, I started to get a sore throat, as I first felt it, I decided to immediately self- isolate myself. I alerted work and booked myself in for staff swabbing. The next day I developed a fever, this fever lasted around one week with my sore throat. Most of my time being ill was spent in my bed. I could not move literally. I had aches and pain, I felt nauseous at times and lost my senses I couldn’t taste or smell anything which really stressed me out. The night before receiving my swab results, I was so anxious, I couldn’t sleep. ⁣
⁣

A few aspiring Canadian pilots have been asking me the question, "Is it even worth getting my pilot's license anymore?" And that's a great question, especially considering the state the industry is in right now.⁣
⁣⁣⁣
YES. It still is. We all know that the cost of flying is steadily going up. Flight schools are raising their rental costs, insurance is creeping up, etc. If you've budgeted out the money for a private pilot's license, that's an incredible step forward towards your goal of being a commercial pilot. GET THAT LICENSE! :) It's a 'piece of paper' that you'll be able to hang on to the rest of you life. No one will be able to take that accomplishment away from you. And now, there's no rush to get all of your licenses done at once, so take the time to enjoy the process, and take that first step forward. As soon as flight schools open back up again, there's no reason why you shouldn't set off to become a private pilot.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
After that, I'd recommend getting your instrument rating for the same reasons.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Seasoned pilots, what's all of your opinions on this? 🤔🛩️⁣⁣⁣

Anyone experiencing “Zoom-zaustion”? Have you found yourself sitting for hours at time staring at a computer screen? Your Athletic Medicine staff has and we wanted to share with you some simple exercises that you can do to help relieve those tight hip flexors, sore backs and achy necks:
•
•
1️⃣ Cervical Retraction: In a sitting/standing/lying down position draw your head straight back and the chin down slightly, creating a “double chin.” Hold this position for 1-2 sec and release. Complete 1-2 sets of 10 reps.
•
•
2️⃣ Thoracic Extension over a chair: Sit in a chair that has a lower back. Looking up towards the ceiling, cross hands over your chest or behind your head and bend backwards over the chair until you feel a stretch. Hold the stretch for 10-15 sec and repeat 2-3 times. You can adjust your positioning so that you can hit different levels of your thoracic spine as needed.
•
•
 3️⃣ Reverse Snow Angels: Sit with back against a wall. Start with arms overhead and slowly move downwards while trying to keep wrists, elbows against the wall. Avoid any hyperextension of your low back. Repeat 10-15 times.
•
•
 4️⃣ Hip Flexor Stretch: Position yourself in a tall ½ kneeling position. Squeeze glute on leg that is back and push hip forward. Avoid hyperextending your low back. Hold for 15-20 sec. Add in upper body overhead reach, overhead lateral reach or straight arm twist to opposite side to hit all planes!
•
•
5️⃣ Hamstring Stretch: Prop leg up on an elevated surface (chair, couch, low table). Bend at your hips and reach towards your toes. Then try reaching outward towards the pinky toes and inward towards the big toe. Hold each for 15-20 sec.
•
•
We are recommending that these be completed at least once an hour for maximal effects. Study hard and good luck with finals!

● Scientists created a monoclonal antibody that can defeat the new coronavirus in the lab, an early but promising step in efforts to find treatments and curb the pandemic’s spread.⠀
⠀
● The experimental antibody may help prevent or treat Covid-19 and related diseases, either alone or in a drug combination, according to a study published Monday in the journal Nature Communications. More research is needed to see if the findings are confirmed in a clinical setting, Berend-Jan Bosch of Utrecht University in the Netherlands and colleagues wrote in the paper.⠀
⠀
● The antibody known as 47D11 targets the spike protein that gives the new coronavirus a crown-like shape and lets it enter human cells. In the Utrecht experiments, it didn’t just defeat the virus responsible for Covid-19 but also a cousin equipped with similar spike proteins, which causes Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome, or SARS.⠀
